AGI -&nbsp; In Britain exotic spiders with more different colors, sizes and aspects emerge, in all 50 non-autochthonous species coming from distant lands with the global movement of goods and people. To promote their proliferation is the global warming that produces an increasingly hospitable climate Beyond the Channel. As reported by the newspaper The Guardian>, among the new species there is a skip spider, identified on the Penryn campus of the University of Exeter, in Cornwall. Its closest known 'parent' is the Anasaitis milesae, 3-4 mm long, established in the Caribbean, which makes it very likely that this tiny species - along with 17 other species of non-autochthonous skipping spiders - arrived in Britain from distant climates. The new species of spider jumper was discovered by Tylan Berry, on behalf of the British Arachnological Society in Devon and Cornwall, during a "bioblitz", or biological census, on the Penryn campus. The unusual species has been confirmed as new for science and named by Dmitri V Logunov, an expert in skipping spiders, of the zoological institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
&nbsp;
Among the new arrivals, much larger, there is the Zoropsis spinimana, popularly known as the false wolf spider, a Mediterranean species that thrives in the homes of all London. The fake wolf spider spread to the west, to Somerset, and to the north, to Newcastle, since he was first photographed in Britain in 2008. In some cases it received a passage not only on global shipping containers, but also within the campers of returning vacationers from continental Europe. To arouse a stir because of its size and ability, in theory, to pierce the human skin with rapid painful but harmless pinches, there is also the extraordinary tubular spider from the green tusks (Florentine Segestria), which first took foot in Bristol and now is located throughout southern Britain. Cornwall and Devon are the two hot spots for the new spiders: thanks to their ports and mild climate, with the absence of ice cream in some areas, allows exotic species to survive the British winter. Tylan Berry has identified a vast population of another non-autochronous spider: the grey domestic spider (Badumna longinqua) in Plymouth, in an area of 6 square km, where in some places is now the dominant species.
&nbsp;
The spider lives in urban areas, resides in large aggregations and teletextiles - similar to those of some native spiders - on wooden fences and metal signals, including bus stops. This large spider of brown and spider color comes from New South Wales, Australia, and is considered one of the most invasive spider species in some countries where it was accidentally introduced, including Japan, the United States and Brazil. The species in rapid diffusion is not yet well rooted in continental Europe, but has moved rapidly through Britain, since it was first sighted in 2021, first in Washington, Northeast, then in southern Wales, in Nottinghamshire, Camborne and Newquay, in Cornwall. Many of the first sightings had occurred near ports or gardening centres, suggesting that these spiders had arrived on imported plants. "Great Britain's spider fauna, along with the rest of our wildlife, is changing faster than ever. As new exotic species spread, especially outside urban areas, the chances of having an impact on less common autochthonous species," explained Helen Smith, responsible for the conservation of the British Arachnological Society.
&nbsp;
"In addition to competing for prey and housing, these spiders can bring with them new parasites and diseases, a problem well known to gray squirrels and invasive shrimps, but very little studied in spiders," the expert pointed out. Some 15% of autochthonous spider species are already at risk of extinction due to habitat loss and climate change. In the future, non-autochthonous species could increase the risks that local ones will face. In Britain, about 50 non-autochthonous spiders were recorded among the 3,500 non-autochthonous species > established in the country, most of which were inadvertently introduced by the global movement of goods and persons. Only about 10-15% of non-autochthonous species are considered "invasive" - such as gray squirrels, Japanese polygon and Asian hornet or yellow legs - causing an environmental or human negative impact.

